  "risks": {
    "shape": [
      "number_outpatient, number_emergency, and number_inpatient are zero-inflated with rare high counts; synthetic data can flatten utilization tails",
      "diag_1, diag_2, and diag_3 are high-cardinality categorical diagnosis codes with long tails that should not be coerced to continuous numbers",
      "max_glu_serum and A1Cresult are mostly empty but have rare clinically meaningful categories",
      "many medication columns are dominated by No with very rare Up/Down/Steady categories; rare therapy states should not be dropped or amplified",
      "age is an ordinal-encoded age-band column in 0-9, not raw age in years"
    ],
    "trend": [
      "admission_type_id and admission_source_id are strongly coupled encounter-route codes",
      "diag_1, diag_2, and diag_3 form a high-cardinality comorbidity pattern and should not be sampled independently",
      "insulin, diabetesMed, and change jointly describe diabetes therapy/regimen changes",
      "num_medications, time_in_hospital, num_procedures, and num_lab_procedures jointly reflect encounter intensity",
      "prior utilization counts number_outpatient, number_emergency, and number_inpatient jointly encode care history"
    ],
    "privacy": [
      "configured privacy columns are num_lab_procedures, num_medications, number_outpatient, number_emergency, and number_inpatient",
      "there are no raw encounter_id or patient_nbr columns in the processed prompt-context schema, but encounter profiles can still create nearest-neighbor disclosure risk",
      "age, race, gender, admission/discharge/source codes, diagnosis triplets, and medication regimen columns can form narrow patient-encounter fingerprints",
      "high-cardinality diagnosis codes and rare medication states are especially identifying when combined with utilization counts",
      "for 36 feature columns, current theta validation requires col_ps coverage of 18-31 columns; do not use a tiny privacy scope and do not include all feature columns"
    ],
    "utility": [
      "readmitted=1 is the minority positive class at about 46%; synthetic data should preserve positive-class coverage and not convert the task to only <30-day readmission",
      "dropping number_inpatient will substantially weaken readmission classification utility",
      "diagnosis triplets and discharge/admission/source codes provide important utility signal but also raise privacy and high-cardinality risks",
      "using only demographics or sparse medication columns as col_u is too weak for utility",
      "col_u should usually be number_inpatient, number_diagnoses, number_emergency, number_outpatient, discharge_disposition_id, diag_1, diag_2, diag_3, or insulin; never use readmitted"
    ]
  },
